{"agent_id":"79Ig","agent_seq":89,"timestamp":"2026-07-22T17:09:25.083741Z","event":{"type":"CommentAdded","issue_uuid":"028e84f4-cfd0-45aa-8aee-b43ec885d803","comment_uuid":"e085cc76-85b1-41b6-b405-1151fea8f69c","author":"79Ig","content":"CONSUMER RAISE (vsdd-cli relay 2026-07-22, Raise 3) converges on this issue from the consumer side — same design.md incident, seen as a BLOCKED-COMMITS event on their estate: crosslink 0.9's migration deployed a command file with non-strict-YAML frontmatter; mdatron's walk refused it (correctly by its own rules) and blocked the consuming estate's commits over a document mdatron has no mandate to govern. Their asks, in their preference order: (a) ROUTE-TABLE ALLOWLIST — mdatron validates only what a consumer explicitly routes, everything else untouched (they cite Thermite's spec-routes.toml as our own closed-world precedent); (b) ignore list as lighter interim; (c) a stated default — route-only being the closed-world-correct choice, retiring this incident's whole class (an unrouted third-party command file isn't mdatron's to refuse). ASSESSMENT: (a) and my original fix here are the same mechanism — honoring .mdatron/config.yaml file_globs IS the consumer-authored allowlist; the residual decision is the DEFAULT when config is absent (current walk-all vs route-only/empty). Route-only-by-default is a behavior change wanting an SO scope ruling + DESIGN language; honoring file_globs is a straight defect fix (config is committed, deployed by init, and inert). Priority raised: this blocked a consumer's commits in the wild.","created_at":"2026-07-22T17:09:25.067507Z","kind":"note","signed_by":"SHA256:u0VtJEsnHrvNPG5QQKKfDO+Rro/KT/xZqEvahzZTqEA","signature":"U1NIU0lHAAAAAQAAADMAAAALc3NoLWVkMjU1MTkAAAAgOk7MLoVvSEPAWM9VkHKFnHq8O1iEkPSfqY7zLc4I28oAAAARY3Jvc3NsaW5rLWNvbW1lbnQAAAAAAAAABnNoYTUxMgAAAFMAAAALc3NoLWVkMjU1MTkAAABAWISH+jE2wa+NM7fSL8jviHUL10RkHU6DvvyG3/3Yerhh2TSmxB0XlU8X2At8VKa7byo1MMRhx5IWNgoGmzzKCw=="},"signed_by":"SHA256:u0VtJEsnHrvN